[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating class loading issues**\n\nIt seems like coverage reports might only track successful dynamic access and not failures. The context call I covered appears successful with the custom loader returning an object, but I'm missing a driver line failure that isn't reported because it wasn't a successful load. I need to make that load successful even when the Class.forName method fails. However, SQL's Class.forName uses its own class loader, which complicates things. I'll keep exploring possible class loading solutions.\n\n**Exploring Sql driver loading**\n\nI’m thinking about how to call Sql.loadDriver from a different Sql class that's loaded by a custom loader. This might require using reflection or Groovy’s dynamic capabilities. I also need to consider whether to focus my tests on the active original class. However, it seems that coverage instrumentation is probably applied to the loaded Sql class, which might complicate things. I'll keep this in mind as I navigate the implementation.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0657ec834fcc42b20169ffd7138fa4819090190e99c41b08ea\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_9cin6PXSMFUBin-KJoFG-_7HpyltPCGiT_I7IaTxqHednGqJ15Unua2QNB2addY4uyeYPnTnGitFjZ1FhUXrx78KMFwXz4E8PRXqiWEjDS5Qkzls5jsrsOq6VYN5bb5lr-xclbG1rHhE_EnWb1ahQW85yGhovJGtTi9xq654XcI1Gtm4h1sWt673k5L6aAYmXRSu5sbkjdGCl7jmyp0aeo4sEjc8KjD6hJlryx2BKU7VBoj_Ifin9y6umWWNIWO2Y8kgFYYHSEfRgbWkqX5LJ2CrURXN2lAyObaJRhZiSrthuG3tcjyI4K6De5YdDMpga-XAWhMQoyc4fsWVFYuO1ljZYliM0nzL1CyW1WTS5HCzFQvCO3WJn_J1L8Y9vykRr71ELAMbeo7aOTeUeDdOfhTr043ac4upDMuR-IT6XAYErf7z3ItQzB5bKnwmShiBQpIHhkNt4EVgrGnx4c7bucnv8HNsEzw0nteltvXhj3WTAhUM871vP7p8yN-OqrlqMZ2Mp9YHA-W4QB1H0_b2Phsn5sv2mJk_jKy9AHVwV0SVZ0OOxCNrOLg_70vfi6YWXzhpuKxioF4sIUBpVsDUt4-AoO2RAZZ8USgKQ3-MhrMZNsmwCJ8Nl0L_RDrUb_jSCCxx86qFxJPu1qgr3U6yqrmZoUMzS0qtDNnlxOdAEfvaIrDuse2GPWwYAc7_gdxHZXbACwcUSxfSz8V-_IepnMerr6Z08dbS3