that there might be a flaw in our override for `Class.forName` detection. When we call `Class.forName(driverClassName)` within isolated SQL class loader contexts, it directly invokes `loadClass(String, false)`. This could lead to throwing a `ClassNotFoundException`. I'm analyzing the stack trace that includes `Class.forName`, and it seems perplexing that we have a context `ClassNotFoundException` followed by a success at line 738. It's worth investigating further!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Groovy implementation**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how in Groovy, the interface and implementation can coexist as top-level in the same file. The child loader should be able to load the implementation bytecode resource. But I wonder if the current isolated usage of InvokerHelper on the Sql class is direct enough. Line coverage for dynamic access seems like it shouldn’t matter in this case. Still, I notice this approach also loads Sql from a URL, which adds another layer to consider.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_L8bRi7lDEnOmfJ39vL7uPkHh|fc_0657ec834fcc42b20169ffd7f4a0e4819099c992006e2539d2", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.groovy/groovy-sql/4.0.24/src/test/groovy/org_apache_groovy/groovy_sql/GroovySqlSqlTest.groovy", "edits": [{"oldText": "public final class IsolatedSqlClassLoader extends ClassLoader {\n    static final String SQL_CLASS_NAME = 'groovy.sql.Sql'\n\n    private final String driverClassName\n    int sqlClassLoaderDriverLoads\n\n    IsolatedSqlClassLoader(String driverClassName) {\n        super(Sql.class.getClassLoader())\n        this.driverClassName = driverClassName\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n        if (driverClassName.equals(name)) {\n            if (calledFromClassForName()) {\n                throw new ClassNotFoundException(name)\n            }\n            sqlClassLoaderDriverLoads++\n            return Object\n        }\n        if (name.equals(SQL_CLASS_NAME) || name.startsWith(SQL_CLASS_NAME + '$')) {\n            Class<?> loadedClass = findLoadedClass(name)\n            if (loadedClass == null) {\n                loadedClass = defineClassFromParentResource(name)\n            }\n            if (resolve) {\n                resolveClass(loadedClass)\n            }\n            return loadedClass\n        }\n        return super.loadClass(name, resolve)\n    }\n\n    private Class<?> defineClassFromParentResource(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n        String resourceName = name.replace('.', '/') + '.class'\n        InputStream inputStream = getParent().getResourceAsStream(resourceName)\n        if (inputStream == null) {\n            throw new ClassNotFoundException(name)\n        }\n        try (InputStream closeableInputStream = inputStream) {\n            byte[] bytecode = closeableInputStream.readAllBytes()\n            return defineClass(name, bytecode, 0, bytecode.length)\n        } catch (IOException exception) {\n            ClassNotFoundException classNotFoundException = new ClassNotFoundException(name)\n            classNotFoundException.initCause(exception)\n            throw classNotFoundException\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static boolean calledFromClassForName() {", "newText": "public final class IsolatedSqlClassLoader extends URLClassLoader {\n    static final String SQL_CLASS_NAME = 'groovy.sql.Sql'\n\n    private final String driverClassName\n    int sqlClassLoaderDriverLoads\n\n    IsolatedSqlClassLoader(String driverClassName) {\n        super([Sql.protectionDomain.codeSource.location] as URL[], Sql.class.getClassLoader())\n        this.driverClassName = driverClassName\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n        if (driverClassName.equals(name)) {\n            if (calledFromClassForName()) {\n                throw new ClassNotFoundException(na